"is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PD", "obj": "disease", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 845, "end": 847}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000544", "mim:104300"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Alzheimer&#39;s disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999985098838806, "span": {"begin": 858, "end": 881}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017096"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prion disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999959468841553, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 896}}, {"id": ["CL:0000129"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microglia", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8265409469604492, "span": {"begin": 1172, "end": 1181}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "astrocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.841301679611206, "span": {"begin": 1186, "end": 1196}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010300"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Parkinson&#39;s disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999858140945435, "span": {"begin": 1220, "end": 1243}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.554776668548584, "span": {"begin": 1311, "end": 1318}}, {"id": ["CL:0000129"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microglia", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6915263533592224, "span": {"begin": 1355, "end": 1364}}, {"id": ["CL:0002629"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "reactive microglia", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.817844033241272, "span": {"begin": 1437, "end": 1455}}, {"id": ["mim:168600"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PD", "obj": "disease", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1507, "end": 1509}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9878956079483032, "span": {"begin": 1510, "end": 1518}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "people", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8319220542907715, "span": {"begin": 1525, "end": 1531}}, {"id": ["mesh:D015632"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MPTP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9972785115242004, "span": {"begin": 1560, "end": 1564}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "co-cultures", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.5903457403182983, "span": {"begin": 1710, "end": 1721}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7988199591636658, "span": {"begin": 1725, "end": 1732}}, {"id": ["CL:0000129"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microglia", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7305501103401184, "span": {"begin": 1737, "end": 1746}}, {"id": ["mesh:D015632"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MPTP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991931319236755, "span": {"begin": 1821, "end": 1825}}], "text": "Kreutzberg and coworkers (1995, 1996) showed that neuronal injury generally leads to activation of microglia and astrocytes. This is a general phenomenon: for instance it is always observed in ischemic damage (stroke; often in the form of glial activation following neuronal injury (Villa 2007)) as well as in stab or freeze injuries (Allahyari and Garcia, 2015). It is also observed regularly when neurons are killed by highly specific neurotoxicants that do not affect glia directly, such as injection of quinolinic acid or of 6-hydroxydopamine into the striatum (Hernandez-Baltazar et al., 2013; Arlicot et al., 2014). The vicious circle of neuronal injury triggering glial activation and glial activation triggering/enhancing neurodegeneration is often assumed to be a key element in the pathogenesis of neurodegenerative diseases, not just PD, but also Alzheimer&#39;s disease, prion disease and many others(Hirsch and Hunot, 2009; Tansey and Goldberg, 2009; Griffin et al., 1998; McGeer and Mc Geer, 1998; Blasko et al., 2004; Cacquevel et al., 2004; Rubio-Perez and Morillas-Ruiz, 2012; Thundyil and Lim, 2014; Barbeito et al., 2010).  Innate immune system, mainly microglia and astrocytes is primary involved in Parkinson&#39;s disease the(Lucin et al. 2009, Glass et al. 20101, Rocha et al. 2012), and neurons are knowns to actively regulate the microglia response to stress (Mott et al. 2004, Cardona et al. 2006). Presence of reactive microglia has been observed in post-mortem brain tissue from PD patients or in people following intoxication with MPTP as well as in animal models of PD (McGeer et al. 1988, Langston et al. 1999, McGeer et al. 2003, Czlonkowska et al. 1996, Walsh et al. 2011). In co-cultures of neurons and microglia neuronal damage/cell death triggers microglia activation that potentiates MPTP-induced neuronal injury (Gao et al. 2003).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:20:56 +0000 2026"}